{"id":"1409.1100","submitter":"Misha Verbitsky","authors":"Andrey Soldatenkov, Misha Verbitsky","title":"k-symplectic structures and absolutely trianalytic subvarieties in\n  hyperkahler manifolds","comments":"23 pages, v. 3.2, published version; statement of Proposition 2.11\n  and Corollary 2.12 amended because of an error/misprint","journal-ref":"J. Geom. Phys. 92 (2015), 147-156","doi":"10.1016/j.geomphys.2014.11.011","report-no":null,"categories":"math.AG math.DG","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Let $(M,I,J,K)$ be a hyperkahler manifold, and $Z\\subset (M,I)$ a complex\nsubvariety in $(M,I)$. We say that $Z$ is trianalytic if it is complex analytic\nwith respect to $J$ and $K$, and absolutely trianalytic if it is trianalytic\nwith respect to any hyperk\\\"ahler triple of complex structures $(M,I,J',K')$\ncontaining $I$. For a generic complex structure $I$ on $M$, all complex\nsubvarieties of $(M,I)$ are absolutely trianalytic. It is known that a\nnormalization $Z'$ of a trianalytic subvariety is smooth; we prove that\n$b_2(Z')$ is no smaller than $b_2(M)$ when $M$ has maximal holonomy (that is,\n$M$ is IHS). To study absolutely trianalytic subvarieties further, we define a\nnew geometric structure, called k-symplectic structure; this structure is a\ngeneralization of the hypersymplectic structure. A k-symplectic structure on a\n2d-dimensional manifold $X$ is a k-dimensional space $R$ of closed 2-forms on\n$X$ which all have rank 2d or d. It is called non-degenerate if the set of all\ndegenerate forms in $R$ is a smooth, non-degenerate quadric hypersurface in\n$R$. We consider absolutely trianalytic tori in a hyperkahler manifold $M$ of\nmaximal holonomy. We prove that any such torus is equipped with a\nnon-degenerate k-symplectic structure, where $k=b_2(M)$. We show that the\ntangent bundle $TX$ of a k-symplectic manifold is a Clifford module over a\nClifford algebra $Cl(k-1)$. Then an absolutely trianalytic torus in a\nhyperkahler manifold $M$ with $b_2(M)\\geq 2r+1$ is at least\n$2^{r-1}$-dimensional.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Sep 2014 14:20:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 7 Oct 2014 12:30:22 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 9 Feb 2019 00:52:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-02-12"}
